                  <handDesc>
                  <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                  <seg type="rubrication">
                  <foreign xml:lang="gez">ኢግዚአብሔር፡</foreign>
                  <foreign xml:lang="gez">ማርያም፡</foreign>
                  </seg>
                  <desc>The word God is rubricated in the first three works; the word Mary is rubricated in the final two works</desc>
                  <desc>Columetric layout of text: <locus target="#105r" facs="109">fols. 105r, </locus> (Ps. 148r); <locus target="#106r" facs="110">106r, </locus> (Ps. 150); <locus target="#114v #115r" facs="119">114v, 115r</locus> (tenth biblical canticle)</desc>
                  </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                  <decoNote type="frame" xml:id="d1">
                  Decorative designs:
                  a line of alternating red and black dots appears after every ten psalms;
                  <locus target="#49r #139r" facs="053 143">fols. 49r, 139r</locus> (multiple full stops between lines of red and black dots)
                  </decoNote>
                </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                  <list>
                    <item xml:id="a1">
                    <locus target="#140v" facs="145">Fol. 140v</locus>
                    <desc type="RecordTransaction">
                    Note of transaction for the sale of the codex
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e1">
                    <desc>
                      The de luxe features in the codex (two-tone head band and tail band, trimmed turn-ins, fabric visible between the turn-ins, fine hand, even parchment) and the Hebraic edition of the Song of Songs would indicate that this codex was produced in the government scriptorium
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e2">
                    <desc>
                    Numbered quires: quires 1–14
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e3">
                    <locus target="#5r #6r #16r #20r #22r" facs="009 010 020 024 026">Fols. 5r, 6r, 16r, 20r, 22r</locus>
                    <desc>etc., words of text are written interlinearly
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e4">
                    <locus target="#25v #69r #91v #93r #103r" facs="030 073 096 097 107">Fols. 25v, 69r, 91v, 93r, 103r</locus>
                    <desc>etc., lines of text are written interlinearly
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e5">
                    <locus target="#132r" facs="136"> f. 132r, col. 1, line 9</locus>
                    <locus target="#137v" facs="142"> f. 137v, col. 2, line 8</locus>
                    <locus target="#137r" facs="141"> f. 137r, col. 2, line 20</locus>
                    <desc>
                    lines of text are written in the upper margin with a symbol (+) marking the location where the text is to be inserted (132r; 137v), and in another case where the symbol (┴) is used (137r);
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e6">
                    <locus target="#iir(ecto) #5v #24v #26v #33r" facs="002 010 029 031 037">Fols. iir(ecto), 5v, 24v, 26v, 33r</locus>
                    <desc>etc., text has been removed
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e7">
                    <desc>
                    There is very little line wrapping. The scribe has addressed the challenge primarily by the selection of a good aspect ratio and font size, but also through the liberal use of micrography to complete lines that would be too long
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                  </list>
                </additions>
                <bindingDesc>
                  <binding xml:id="binding" contemporary="true">
                    <decoNote xml:id="b1">Parchment, four Coptic chain stitches attached with bridle attachments to rough-hewn boards of the traditional wood, covered with tooled leather with linen beneath the pastedowns, headband and tailband.</decoNote>
                    <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="bindingMaterial">
                      <material key="parchment"/>
                      <material key="wood"/>
                      <material key="leather"/>
                      <material key="textile"/>
                    </decoNote>
                  </binding>
                </bindingDesc>
